\subsection{Interplay between Informed and uninformed}
Fisher Black identifies noise as ``the arbitrary element in expectations'' \citet[p.529]{BlackNoise}. He cites a number of ways that noise affects the trading in financial markets.  He speaks about people trading on noise over information; he says that noise makes financial markets possible but imperfect. The more noise-traders that there are, the more liqiity and the easier to trade; the more noise-traders the higher the level of inefficiency in the market and the more likely that prices will be driven from their fundamental value. He suggest that the noise will limit the scope for complete arbitrage and that it will be difficult to distinguish between noise and information traders. 

