\subsection{why this is important}
The nature of speculation and the role of noise-traders has become increasingly imporant since the golbal financial crisis (GFC).  There are a number of comtemporary questions where the role and nature of speculation is at the center of the debate.  Regulations or taxes that reduce the reduce the amount of speculation have generally been considered to be helpful in reducing risk and encouraging more long-term attitudes towards investment.  However, where these measures reduce liquidity, higher risk and an increase in other costs may provide an countervailing force.  For example, the so-called \emph{Volcker Rule} would prevent US inventment banks trading on their own-account.  This, it has been argued, will reduce liquidity in the bond market by causing investment banks to hold lower levels of bond inventory on their books.  This may increase the amount of \emph{price slippage} when final investor adjust their positions.  

